{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U87GaDoH65HZk8Hf8CqTc6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Comtron Inc. — Product Research\n     2→\n     3→Researched: 2026-02-14\n     4→Developer website: http://www.medgenehr.com/\n     5→\n     6→## Overview\n     7→\n     8→Comtron Inc. (doing business as Comtron USA) is a healthcare software company founded in 1987 and based in Great Neck, New York. The company develops Medgen EHR and LABGEN LIS (Laboratory Information System), along with revenue cycle management (RCM) services. In August 2024, MEDFAR Clinical Solutions — a Canadian EMR company that develops the MYLE Integrated Care Platform (described as the fastest-growing EMR in Canada) — announced the successful integration of Comtron, marking MEDFAR's entry into the U.S. primary care market. The Medgen EHR website now carries MEDFAR branding, and the About page describes the combined entity as serving \"over 15,000 providers and supporting 20 million patient interactions each year.\"\n     9→\n    10→Comtron/MEDFAR targets ambulatory physician practices across multiple specialties, with particular emphasis on two niche markets: **addiction medicine / opioid treatment programs** (OTPs) and **OB/GYN practices**. The company also offers specialty-specific templates for behavioral health, cardiology, gastroenterology, internal medicine, psychiatry, podiatry, pediatrics, pulmonary, and sleep medicine. The primary contact listed on CHPL is David DeBlasio (deblasio@comtronusa.com). The company is small — with only 3 reviews on Capterra and limited third-party analyst coverage, it appears to be a niche vendor rather than a major market player.\n    11→\n    12→## Product: Medgen EHR\n    13→\n    14→CHPL ID: 10986 (Version 9, certified 2022-09-15)\n    15→\n    16→### What It Is\n    17→\n    18→Medgen EHR is a cloud-based, ONC-certified electronic health record system with integrated billing and practice management. It is certified for 35+ criteria spanning clinical data management (a)(1)–(a)(5), (a)(12), (a)(14); transitions of care (b)(1)–(b)(3); patient portal/view-download-transmit (e)(1); public health reporting (f)(1), (f)(2), (f)(5), (f)(7); and FHIR API access (g)(10). The SED intended user description is \"Healthcare Prescribers, Nurses & Configuration Analysts.\"\n    19→\n    20→The certified module appears to encompass the full product — Medgen EHR is not a component of a larger system. However, Comtron also produces LABGEN LIS as a separate but integrable product, and offers RCM services that work alongside the EHR. Post-acquisition, MEDFAR's MYLE platform is a separate Canadian EMR product; the two products are distinct.\n    21→\n    22→### Users & Market\n    23→\n    24→Medgen EHR targets ambulatory physician practices. Based on vendor materials and third-party listings, the primary user settings include:\n    25→\n    26→- **Opioid Treatment Programs (OTPs) / Substance abuse centers** — a major focus area with deep specialty features for methadone and buprenorphine dispensing\n    27→- **OB/GYN practices** — with dedicated pregnancy monitoring and antepartum/postpartum workflows\n    28→- **General ambulatory clinics** — internal medicine, pediatrics, cardiology, gastroenterology, psychiatry, behavioral health, podiatry, pulmonary, and sleep medicine\n    29→\n    30→Day-to-day users include physicians, nurses, counselors (in addiction medicine settings), billing staff, and practice managers. The MEDFAR About page claims over 15,000 providers across the combined Comtron/MEDFAR entity, though it's unclear how many are Medgen vs. MYLE users. No notable large-system deployments or case studies were found. On Capterra, the product has only 3 reviews (rating: 3.7/5), suggesting a small installed base in the U.S.\n    31→\n    32→### Modules & Functionality\n    33→\n    34→Based on vendor website pages, third-party listings, and review sites, Medgen EHR includes the following modules and capabilities:\n    35→\n    36→**Core Clinical EHR:**\n    37→- Clinical documentation with customizable templates per specialty\n    38→- Problem lists, medication lists, allergies (implied by (a)(1)–(a)(5) certification)\n    39→- Mobile app with Nuance-powered voice dictation for documentation\n    40→- Disease management workflows with patient compliance tracking\n    41→- CPOE (computerized provider order entry) — implied by (a)(1)–(a)(3) certification\n    42→- Clinical decision support — implied by (a)(14) certification\n    43→- Drug interaction checking — implied by (a)(4) certification\n    44→\n    45→**E-Prescribing:**\n    46→- Electronic prescribing including controlled substances schedules\n   133→- **Billing & financial data**: Claims, charges, payments, insurance eligibility records, EDI transactions, invoices, referral authorizations, CPT-coded procedures\n   134→- **Documents**: Scanned documents (MedScan), faxes, clinical forms, consent/authorization templates\n   135→- **Patient portal data**: Patient-facing messages, portal access records, appointment reminders\n   136→- **Addiction medicine data**: Controlled substance inventory (lot numbers, bottle volumes, dispensing records, spillage), drug screening results, dosing records, service plans, incident reports, bio-psychosocial assessments, counselor notes, discharge records\n   137→- **OB/GYN data**: Antepartum/postpartum records, pregnancy progress notes, EFW calculations, EDD records, of care**: C-CDA documents (sent and received)\n   140→- **Audit data**: Complete audit trails per the vendor website\n   141→- **Internal communications**: Secure messages, faxes via message center\n   142→\n   143→The billing and practice management features are described as fully integrated into the EHR, not as a separate product. LABGEN LIS is a separate product with its own interfaces but does integrate with Medgen EHR for result delivery. Revenue cycle management services are offered as a service layer on top of the billing module.\n   144→\n   145→---\n   146→\n   147→## Related Product: LABGEN LIS\n   148→\n   149→LABGEN LIS is a separate Laboratory Information System product from Comtron/MEDFAR. It is not part of the Medgen EHR certification but is marketed alongside it and integrates with it. LABGEN includes physician, sales rep, and patient portals; interfaces with lab analyzers; and supports clinical, molecular, and pathology testing modules. It has its own RCM billing portal. LABGEN is relevant context because lab data may flow between LABGEN and Medgen EHR, but the EHI export obligation falls on the certified Medgen EHR product, not on LABGEN separately.\n   150→\n   151→## Research Gaps\n   152→\n   153→- **Customer count**: The \"15,000 providers\" figure is for the combined MEDFAR/Comtron entity across the U.S. and Canada; the Medgen-specific U.S. install base is unclear.\n   154→- **Telehealth**: Conflicting information on whether telemedicine is included (vendor says yes, one third-party says no).\n   155→- **Behavioral health depth**: While behavioral health is listed as a supported specialty, the vendor doesn't describe behavioral-health-specific features as deeply as addiction medicine or OB/GYN. Clinical Data\nArchitecture is a markup standard developed by Health Level 7 International. It defines the structure of\nmedical records, including progress and discharge summaries.\n\nCCDA is an XML based standard encoding document for easy data exchange. It’s describes the syntax\nand provides a frame work specifying the full semantics of patient’s clinical document. The first CCDA\ndocument was approved in 2000.\nCDA is used across healthcare organizations, including clinics, hospitals, and regulatory authorities. If client share a patient's clinical information with other providers, as well as with systems\nthat store patient data, you can create a CCDA document through our Medgen Backup Utility API. {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RyFqoHLXPEYJpjy5CJmJWa","type":"tool_result","content":"• AllergyType\n• Allergy Coded\n• AllergyStatus\n• Allergy Reaction\nTimestamp:\nThe below equates to the time the concern was authored in the patient's chart. This may frequently be\nan EHR timestamp. For below example concern was documented on May 10, 1980\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n22\n\n\fAllergyType:\nThis below represents code was selected to negate any allergy. For no known drug allergies, code\n416098002 would be more appropriate.\n\nAllergyCoded:\nRxNorm is used to report specific drug allergies. Note to use SNOMED CT for drug classes. Best practice\nis to report drug allergies at ingredient level (e.g. penicillin) not at the administration level (e.g. 10mg\ntablet)\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n23\n\n\fAllergy Status:\n\nThis section describes to status of the allergy like active or inactive.\n\nAllergy Reaction:\nThis specifies that the allergy reaction is related to a hives. The following constraints reflect limitations\nin the base CDA R2 specification.\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n24\n\n\fCarePlan:\nA Care Plan is a consensus-driven dynamic plan that represents a patient’s and Care Team Members’\nprioritized concerns, goals, and planned interventions. It serves as a blueprint shared by all Care Team\nMembers (including the patient, their caregivers and providers), to guide the patient’s care. A Care\nPlan integrates multiple interventions proposed by multiple providers and disciplines for multiple\nconditions.\nThe CDA Care Plan represents an instance of this dynamic Care Plan at a point in time. The CDA document itself\nis NOT dynamic. Key differentiators between a Care Plan CDA and CCD (another “snapshot in time” document):\n\nRequired:\n\n\n\nHealth Concerns\nInterventions\n\nOptional:\n\n\n\nGoal\nOutcomes\n\nUSCDI Data Class\nCarePaln\n\nData elements included in the section\n Code specifying whether the item is a goal or a plan\n\n\n\nof care\nGoal or care plan text\nProblem name for problem-based instructions\n\nSample CCDA for CarePlan:\n\nCarePlan Data elements section Overview\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n25\n\n\fXPath\nSection\ntemplateId\n@root\n@extension\nCode\n@code\n@codeSystem\nsection\ntext\nentry\n@typeCode\n\nValue\n\n2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.1 .15\n\n2015-08-01\nurn:oid:2.16.840.1.113762.1.4 .1099.10 (Care Plan\nDocument Type)\nurn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.5.1 11 (HL7RoleCode) =\n2.16.840.1.113883.5.111\nGoals Section (identifier: urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.10.\n20.22.2.60\n\nurn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.1.1 1.11610\n(x_ActRelationshipDocument)\n\nHealth Concerns:\nThe below describes the patient’s general health using an HL7 defined SNOMED code subset. Examples\ninclude alive and well, chronically ill, in remission, general health poor, etc.\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n26\n\n\fAuthenticator\nThe authenticator identifies a participant or participants who attest to the accuracy of the information in the\ndocument.\n\nCare plan Review:\nThis participant represents the Care Plan review. If the date in the time element is in the past, then this\nreview has already taken place. If the date in the time element is in the future, then this is the date of\nthe next scheduled review. This example shows a Care Plan Review that has already taken place.\n\nCareTeam\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n27\n\n\fThe Care Team Section is used to share historical and current Care Team information. A Care Team can exist\nover time such as a longitudinal care team which includes historical members that may be active or inactive on\nthe care team as needed. Or a Care Team, such as a rehabilitation team, may exist to address a person's needs\nassociated with a particular care event, or a team can be based on addressing a specific condition.\n\nRequired:\n\n\nActivity\n\nOptional:\n\n\nCare team organizer\n\nUSCDI Data Class\nCare Team\n\nData elements included in the section\n Care Team Member Name\n Member Identifier\n Member Role\n Location\n Telecom\n\nCCDA template for Care Team:\n\nMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n28\n\n\fMedgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\n\n29\n\n\fCare Team Section Overview\nXPath\nSection\ntemplateId\n@root\n@extension\nCode\n@code\n@codeSystem\ntitle\ntext\nentry\nact\n\nValue\n\n2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.2 .500\n2022-06-01\nurn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.6.1 (LOINC) = 85847-2\nurn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.6.1\n2.16.840.1.113883.6.1\n\nAllergy Concern Act (V3) (identifier\nurn hl7ii: 2.16.840.1.113883.1 0.20.22.4.30:201508-01\n\nThis section will describe the care team provider. {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Ruy8v6y8VK386JCJzFf8mM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SJU8MkYbmyDJWpCG3THxLH","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/jmandel/hobby/ehi-export-analysis/results/comtron-inc/ehi-export-report.md","content":"# Comtron Inc. — EHI Export Documentation\n\nCollected: 2026-02-14\n\n## Source\n- Registered URL: https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\n- CHPL IDs: 10986\n- Product: Medgen EHR, Version 9\n- Certification date: 2022-09-15\n\n## Navigation Journal\n\nThe registered URL is a direct PDF download. No navigation was required.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sI -L \"https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\" \\\n  -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/120.0.0.0 Safari/537.36'\n```\n\nResponse: HTTP/2 200, Content-Type: application/pdf, Content-Length: 2977613. Server is Microsoft-IIS/10.0 with ASP.NET. No redirects.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\" \\\n  -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/120.0.0.0 Safari/537.36' \\\n  -o MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\n```\n\nVerified: `file` identifies it as \"PDF document, version 1.5, 79 page(s)\". Author: Naveen Malla. Created with Microsoft Word 2016 on September 13, 2023.\n\n## What Was Found\n\nThe PDF is titled **\"Medgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\"** (July 2023, 79 pages). It documents a Windows desktop application called \"Medgen Backup Utility\" (`MedBackup_Utility.exe`) that connects to the Medgen EHR cloud service and exports patient data. The document covers:\n\n### Export Mechanism\nThe utility is a Windows MSI-installable desktop application. After installation, the user logs in with Medgen EHR credentials, selects a practice/office, and configures backup criteria:\n- **All Patients**: exports every patient in the practice\n- **By Date/Time Range**: exports patients within a specified date range\n- **By Patient ID Code**: exports selected individual patients\n\nThe utility supports optional AES encryption of exported files, and can be scheduled for automated backup via Windows Task Scheduler using an `AUTORUN <PRACTICE CODE>` command-line argument.\n\n### Export Format — Two Components\n\n**1. C-CDA XML documents (per patient):** Each patient gets an XML file conforming to C-CDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture). The document extensively describes the C-CDA sections included, with XML template IDs, XPath structure, and USCDI data class mappings for each section:\n\n| C-CDA Section | USCDI Data Class | Key Data Elements |\n|---|---|---|\n| Allergy Intolerance | Allergies & Intolerance | Drug allergies, reactions |\n| CarePlan | CarePlan | Health concerns, interventions, goals |\n| CareTeam | Care Team | Member name, identifier, role, location, telecom |\n| Problems | Problems | Active/resolved problems, diagnosis dates, resolution dates |\n| Medication | Medication | Medications, dose, indication, fill status |\n| Immunization | Immunization | Vaccination status, codes |\n| Functional Status | Functional Status | Health concerns, functional status, smoking status |\n| Cognitive Status | Cognitive Status | Physical, cognitive, intellectual, psychiatric disabilities |\n| Result Section Data | Results | Tests, values/results |\n| Vital Signs | Vital Signs | BP, heart rate, respiratory rate, temperature, height, weight, pulse ox, O2 concentration |\n| Social History | Social History | Name, DOB, birth sex, address, telecom, smoking status |\n| Implant or Device | Implant/Device | UDI device data |\n| History of Encounter | Encounters | Encounter type, diagnosis, time, location |\n| Goals | Goals | Patient goals |\n| Procedure | Procedure | Procedures performed |\n| Clinical Notes | Clinical Notes | Consultation notes, discharge summaries, procedure notes, progress notes, test reports |\n\n**2. Patient document ZIP files:** Each patient also gets a ZIP file containing scanned/attached documents (lab reports, patient education materials, etc.) with a structured filename pattern: `{docno}_{date}_{idcode}_{firstname}_{lastname}_{dob}_{provider}_{description}.{ext}`\n\n**3. Additional CSV files (pp. 72–77):** The guide documents supplementary CSV exports that go beyond C-CDA. These are described with full column-level data dictionaries:\n\n- **patients.csv** (22 columns): Demographics, address, phone numbers, email, SSN, and primary/secondary insurance details (code, name, policy number)\n- **appointments.csv** (12 columns): Appointment date, time, duration, reason, notes, provider, office\n- **pharmacy.csv** (7 columns): Patient-pharmacy associations with NCPDPID identifiers\n- **comments.csv** (6 columns): Patient comments/alerts with dates and color coding\n- **Transactions.csv** (117 columns): Comprehensive billing/financial data including claims, procedure codes with modifiers, charges, payments, deductibles, copays, adjustments, balances (primary/other/patient), up to 12 diagnosis codes, insurance details (primary and secondary with policy/group/dates), action notes, claim status/substatus, provider info, office info, and sales group fields\n\n### Bulk Export Note\nThe final page states: \"For a bulk data export of full patient populations please contact a Medgen support team member: medgensupport@comtronusa.com\" — suggesting the utility documented here may handle individual or filtered exports, with population-level bulk export requiring vendor assistance.\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\n\nComtron's approach is **notably better than average** for a small vendor. Rather than simply pointing to their FHIR API or repackaging a C-CDA export alone, they have created a **hybrid export** that combines C-CDA XML (for standardized clinical data) with supplementary CSV files (for data that doesn't fit neatly into C-CDA).\n\n**Clearly covered domains:**\n- **Clinical records**: Problems, medications, allergies, vital signs, immunizations, clinical notes, care plans, care teams, goals, procedures, functional/cognitive status — all via C-CDA\n- **Lab/imaging results**: Result Section Data in C-CDA covers lab and imaging observations\n- **Encounters**: History of encounters with diagnosis, type, time, location\n- **Devices/implants**: UDI device data via C-CDA\n- **Patient demographics**: Covered in both C-CDA header and patients.csv (with more detail in CSV including SSN, insurance)\n- **Insurance/payer data**: Primary and secondary insurance in patients.csv, plus extensive insurance detail in Transactions.csv\n- **Billing/financial data**: Transactions.csv is remarkably comprehensive with 117 columns covering claims, charges, payments, adjustments, diagnosis codes, insurance billing details, and action notes\n- **Appointments/scheduling**: appointments.csv covers appointment scheduling data\n- **Pharmacy associations**: pharmacy.csv\n- **Patient comments/alerts**: comments.csv\n- **Patient documents**: Scanned documents exported as ZIP files\n\n**Domains that appear missing or uncovered:**\n- **Addiction medicine data**: This is Medgen's signature specialty module — methadone/buprenorphine dispensing records, controlled substance inventory, drug screening panels, dosing records, service plans, incident reports, bio-psychosocial assessments, counselor notes. None of this appears in the export documentation. This is a significant gap given it's a core differentiating feature.\n- **OB/GYN specialty data**: Antepartum/postpartum records, pregnancy tracking, EFW calculations, EDD records, ultrasound reports, high-risk care plans, OB questionnaires — none documented in the export.\n- **E-prescribing history**: While medications are in C-CDA, the prescription transmission history, controlled substance prescriptions (EPCS), and pharmacy refill requests are not explicitly mentioned.\n- **Audit trails**: The vendor website advertises \"complete audit trails\" but the export documentation doesn't mention audit log export.\n- **Internal messaging**: Secure messages between providers, e-fax records — not mentioned.\n- **Patient portal data**: Portal access records, patient-provider messages — not mentioned.\n- **Document scanning metadata**: While scanned documents are exported as files in ZIPs, the MedScan metadata (scan dates, categories, indexing) is not documented.\n- **Referral authorization tracking**: Mentioned as a product feature but absent from export.\n- **Quality reporting data**: PQRS/MIPS quality measure data — not mentioned.\n- **Public health reporting records**: Immunization registry submissions, syndromic surveillance, cancer case reports — the submissions themselves are not in the export.\n\n### Export Format & Standards\n\nThe export uses a **sensible hybrid approach**:\n\n- **C-CDA XML** for standardized clinical data — this is a well-established healthcare interoperability standard. The documentation maps each section to specific C-CDA template IDs and USCDI data classes, showing genuine engagement with the standard rather than superficial compliance.\n- **CSV files** for data that doesn't fit C-CDA (billing, scheduling, pharmacy associations, comments). This is pragmatic — CSV is simple, widely parseable, and appropriate for tabular data.\n- **Document ZIPs** for attached files (lab reports, patient education, etc.)\n\nThe C-CDA portion covers standard USCDI v1 data classes. The CSV portion extends beyond USCDI to include billing, scheduling, and administrative data. A third party could reconstruct a reasonably complete patient clinical and financial record from the combined C-CDA + CSV + documents export, though the absence of specialty module data (addiction medicine, OB/GYN) would leave gaps for practices using those features.\n\nThis is **not** a (g)(10) FHIR API repackaged as (b)(10). The Medgen Backup Utility is a distinct, purpose-built export tool with its own documentation, separate from whatever FHIR endpoint serves the (g)(10) requirement.\n\n### Documentation Quality\n\nThe documentation is **adequate but unpolished**:\n\n- **Strengths**: Step-by-step installation and configuration instructions with screenshots. CSV data dictionaries have column-level specifications (position, column name, description). C-CDA sections are documented with template IDs and XPath structures. The file naming convention is documented.\n- **Weaknesses**: The document mixes generic C-CDA standard education (explaining what C-CDA is, showing XML examples from the standard) with product-specific documentation. Much of the 79 pages is devoted to explaining C-CDA concepts rather than documenting what Medgen specifically exports. The CSV data dictionaries are the most useful product-specific content but only occupy ~6 pages (pp. 72-77). Data types and constraints are not specified for CSV columns. The Transactions.csv \"Description\" column simply repeats the column name for most fields rather than providing actual descriptions.\n- **Missing**: No sample export files. No value set documentation for coded fields. No explanation of how C-CDA and CSV files relate to each other in the export package. No versioning or change history. The \"Software Requirements\" page (p. 78) lists requirements but the content appears truncated/empty — it says requirements are \"needed\" but doesn't list them.\n\nA developer could implement a basic import from the C-CDA files (since C-CDA is a well-documented standard), and could parse the CSVs given the column listings. However, they would need to make assumptions about data types, encoding, and edge cases that aren't documented.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n\n- **C-CDA sections**: Documented at the section and entry level with template IDs. Field-level detail relies on C-CDA standard templates rather than Medgen-specific customizations. No custom extensions or constraints are documented.\n- **CSV files**: Column-level documentation with position numbers, column names, and descriptions. Five CSV files are specified. Data types (string, date, numeric) are not explicitly stated though some can be inferred from descriptions (e.g., \"MM/DD/YYYY\" for dates). No navigation was required.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sI -L \"https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\" \\\n  -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/120.0.0.0 Safari/537.36'\n```\n\nResponse: HTTP/2 200, Content-Type: application/pdf, Content-Length: 2977613. Server is Microsoft-IIS/10.0 with ASP.NET. No redirects.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\" \\\n  -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/120.0.0.0 Safari/537.36' \\\n  -o MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\n```\n\nVerified: `file` identifies it as \"PDF document, version 1.5, 79 page(s)\". Author: Naveen Malla. Created with Microsoft Word 2016 on September 13, 2023.\n\n## What Was Found\n\nThe PDF is titled **\"Medgen Data Export & Backup Utility Guide v1.0\"** (July 2023, 79 pages). It documents a Windows desktop application called \"Medgen Backup Utility\" (`MedBackup_Utility.exe`) that connects to the Medgen EHR cloud service and exports patient data. The document covers:\n\n### Export Mechanism\nThe utility is a Windows MSI-installable desktop application. After installation, the user logs in with Medgen EHR credentials, selects a practice/office, and configures backup criteria:\n- **All Patients**: exports every patient in the practice\n- **By Date/Time Range**: exports patients within a specified date range\n- **By Patient ID Code**: exports selected individual patients\n\nThe utility supports optional AES encryption of exported files, and can be scheduled for automated backup via Windows Task Scheduler using an `AUTORUN <PRACTICE CODE>` command-line argument.\n\n### Export Format — Two Components\n\n**1. C-CDA XML documents (per patient):** Each patient gets an XML file conforming to C-CDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture). The document extensively describes the C-CDA sections included, with XML template IDs, XPath structure, and USCDI data class mappings for each section:\n\n| C-CDA Section | USCDI Data Class | Key Data Elements |\n|---|---|---|\n| Allergy Intolerance | Allergies & Intolerance | Drug allergies, reactions |\n| CarePlan | CarePlan | Health concerns, interventions, goals |\n| CareTeam | Care Team | Member name, identifier, role, location, telecom |\n| Problems | Problems | Active/resolved problems, diagnosis dates, resolution dates |\n| Medication | Medication | Medications, dose, indication, fill status |\n| Immunization | Immunization | Vaccination status, codes |\n| Functional Status | Functional Status | Health concerns, functional status, smoking status |\n| Cognitive Status | Cognitive Status | Physical, cognitive, intellectual, psychiatric disabilities |\n| Result Section Data | Results | Tests, values/results |\n| Vital Signs | Vital Signs | BP, heart rate, respiratory rate, temperature, height, weight, pulse ox, O2 concentration |\n| Social History | Social History | Name, DOB, birth sex, address, telecom, smoking status |\n| Implant or Device | Implant/Device | UDI device data |\n| History of Encounter | Encounters | Encounter type, diagnosis, time, location |\n| Goals | Goals | Patient goals |\n| Procedure | Procedure | Procedures performed |\n| Clinical Notes | Clinical Notes | Consultation notes, discharge summaries, procedure notes, progress notes, test reports |\n\n**2. Patient document ZIP files:** Each patient also gets a ZIP file containing scanned/attached documents (lab reports, patient education materials, etc.) with a structured filename pattern: `{docno}_{date}_{idcode}_{firstname}_{lastname}_{dob}_{provider}_{description}.{ext}`\n\n**3. Additional CSV files (pp. 72–77):** The guide documents supplementary CSV exports that go beyond C-CDA. These are described with full column-level data dictionaries:\n\n- **patients.csv** (22 columns): Demographics, address, phone numbers, email, SSN, and primary/secondary insurance details (code, name, policy number)\n- **appointments.csv** (12 columns): Appointment date, time, duration, reason, notes, provider, office\n- **pharmacy.csv** (7 columns): Patient-pharmacy associations with NCPDPID identifiers\n- **comments.csv** (6 columns): Patient comments/alerts with dates and color coding\n- **Transactions.csv** (117 columns): Comprehensive billing/financial data including claims, procedure codes with modifiers, charges, payments, deductibles, copays, adjustments, balances (primary/other/patient), up to 12 diagnosis codes, insurance details (primary and secondary with policy/group/dates), action notes, claim status/substatus, provider info, office info, and sales group fields\n\n### Bulk Export Note\nThe final page states: \"For a bulk data export of full patient populations please contact a Medgen support team member: medgensupport@comtronusa.com\" — suggesting the utility documented here may handle individual or filtered exports, with population-level bulk export requiring vendor assistance.\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\n\nComtron's approach is **notably better than average** for a small vendor. Rather than simply pointing to their FHIR API or repackaging a C-CDA export alone, they have created a **hybrid export** that combines C-CDA XML (for standardized clinical data) with supplementary CSV files (for data that doesn't fit neatly into C-CDA).\n\n**Clearly covered domains:**\n- **Clinical records**: Problems, medications, allergies, vital signs, immunizations, clinical notes, care plans, care teams, goals, procedures, functional/cognitive status — all via C-CDA\n- **Lab/imaging results**: Result Section Data in C-CDA covers lab and imaging observations\n- **Encounters**: History of encounters with diagnosis, type, time, location\n- **Devices/implants**: UDI device data via C-CDA\n- **Patient demographics**: Covered in both C-CDA header and patients.csv (with more detail in CSV including SSN, insurance)\n- **Insurance/payer data**: Primary and secondary insurance in patients.csv, plus extensive insurance detail in Transactions.csv\n- **Billing/financial data**: Transactions.csv is remarkably comprehensive with 117 columns covering claims, charges, payments, adjustments, diagnosis codes, insurance billing details, and action notes\n- **Appointments/scheduling**: appointments.csv covers appointment scheduling data\n- **Pharmacy associations**: pharmacy.csv\n- **Patient comments/alerts**: comments.csv\n- **Patient documents**: Scanned documents exported as ZIP files\n\n**Domains that appear missing or uncovered:**\n- **Addiction medicine data**: This is Medgen's signature specialty module — methadone/buprenorphine dispensing records, controlled substance inventory, drug screening panels, dosing records, service plans, incident reports, bio-psychosocial assessments, counselor notes. None of this appears in the export documentation. This is a significant gap given it's a core differentiating feature.\n- **OB/GYN specialty data**: Antepartum/postpartum records, pregnancy tracking, EFW calculations, EDD records, ultrasound reports, high-risk care plans, OB questionnaires — none documented in the export.\n- **E-prescribing history**: While medications are in C-CDA, the prescription transmission history, controlled substance prescriptions (EPCS), and pharmacy refill requests are not explicitly mentioned.\n- **Audit trails**: The vendor website advertises \"complete audit trails\" but the export documentation doesn't mention audit log export.\n- **Internal messaging**: Secure messages between providers, e-fax records — not mentioned.\n- **Patient portal data**: Portal access records, patient-provider messages — not mentioned.\n- **Document scanning metadata**: While scanned documents are exported as files in ZIPs, the MedScan metadata (scan dates, categories, indexing) is not documented.\n- **Referral authorization tracking**: Mentioned as a product feature but absent from export.\n- **Quality reporting data**: PQRS/MIPS quality measure data — not mentioned.\n- **Public health reporting records**: Immunization registry submissions, syndromic surveillance, cancer case reports — the submissions themselves are not in the export.\n\n### Export Format & Standards\n\nThe export uses a **sensible hybrid approach**:\n\n- **C-CDA XML** for standardized clinical data — this is a well-established healthcare interoperability standard. The documentation maps each section to specific C-CDA template IDs and USCDI data classes, showing genuine engagement with the standard rather than superficial compliance.\n- **CSV files** for data that doesn't fit C-CDA (billing, scheduling, pharmacy associations, comments). This is pragmatic — CSV is simple, widely parseable, and appropriate for tabular data.\n- **Document ZIPs** for attached files (lab reports, patient education, etc.)\n\nThe C-CDA portion covers standard USCDI v1 data classes. The CSV portion extends beyond USCDI to include billing, scheduling, and administrative data. A third party could reconstruct a reasonably complete patient clinical and financial record from the combined C-CDA + CSV + documents export, though the absence of specialty module data (addiction medicine, OB/GYN) would leave gaps for practices using those features.\n\nThis is **not** a (g)(10) FHIR API repackaged as (b)(10). The Medgen Backup Utility is a distinct, purpose-built export tool with its own documentation, separate from whatever FHIR endpoint serves the (g)(10) requirement.\n\n### Documentation Quality\n\nThe documentation is **adequate but unpolished**:\n\n- **Strengths**: Step-by-step installation and configuration instructions with screenshots. CSV data dictionaries have column-level specifications (position, column name, description). C-CDA sections are documented with template IDs and XPath structures. The file naming convention is documented.\n- **Weaknesses**: The document mixes generic C-CDA standard education (explaining what C-CDA is, showing XML examples from the standard) with product-specific documentation. Much of the 79 pages is devoted to explaining C-CDA concepts rather than documenting what Medgen specifically exports. The CSV data dictionaries are the most useful product-specific content but only occupy ~6 pages (pp. 72-77). Data types and constraints are not specified for CSV columns. The Transactions.csv \"Description\" column simply repeats the column name for most fields rather than providing actual descriptions.\n- **Missing**: No sample export files. No value set documentation for coded fields. No explanation of how C-CDA and CSV files relate to each other in the export package. No versioning or change history. The \"Software Requirements\" page (p. 78) lists requirements but the content appears truncated/empty — it says requirements are \"needed\" but doesn't list them.\n\nA developer could implement a basic import from the C-CDA files (since C-CDA is a well-documented standard), and could parse the CSVs given the column listings. However, they would need to make assumptions about data types, encoding, and edge cases that aren't documented.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n\n- **C-CDA sections**: Documented at the section and entry level with template IDs. Field-level detail relies on C-CDA standard templates rather than Medgen-specific customizations. No custom extensions or constraints are documented.\n- **CSV files**: Column-level documentation with position numbers, column names, and descriptions. Five CSV files are specified. Data types (string, date, numeric) are not explicitly stated though some can be inferred from descriptions (e.g., \"MM/DD/YYYY\" for dates). No value set documentation for coded fields like insurance codes, claim status, etc.\n- **Relationships**: Patient ID (`Id_code`) appears across CSV files, providing the join key. No formal relationship diagram or foreign key documentation.\n- **No versioning**: The guide is v1.0 from July 2023 with no change history.\n\n## Access Summary\n- Final URL (after redirects): https://portal.medgenehr.com/Medgenweb/MedgenBackupUtility.pdf\n- Status: found\n- Required browser: no\n- Navigation complexity: direct_link\n- Anti-bot issues: none\n\n## Obstacles & Dead Ends\n\nNone. The URL returned the PDF directly with no authentication, redirects, or anti-bot challenges.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
